    "body" : "<p>This question was asked before Java 7 release but now, there is another possible way using Java 7 (and above) API:</p>\n\n<pre><code>double random = ThreadLocalRandom.current().nextDouble(min, max);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/ThreadLocalRandom.html#nextDouble(double,%20double)\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>nextDouble</code></a> will return a pseudorandom double value between the minimum (inclusive) and the maximum (exclusive). The bounds are not necessarily <code>int</code>, and can be <code>double</code>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 12719583,
      "reputation" : 163,
      "user_id" : 9240484,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-Uym0n1XWmKU/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAA8Y/Xo3Uf2ZnrgU/s256-rj/photo.jpg",
      "display_name" : "Larson Carter",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/9240484/larson-carter"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 6,
    "last_activity_date" : 1589717386,
    "last_edit_date" : 1589717386,
    "creation_date" : 1524257797,
    "answer_id" : 49949612,
    "question_id" : 3680637,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>import java.util.Random;\n\npublic class MyClass {\n     public static void main(String args[]) {\n          Double min = 0.0;  // Set To Your Desired Min Value\n          Double max = 10.0; // Set To Your Desired Max Value\n          double x = (Math.random() * ((max - min) + 1)) + min;   // This Will Create A Random Number Inbetween Your Min And Max.\n          double xrounded = Math.round(x * 100.0) / 100.0;   // Creates Answer To The Nearest 100 th, You Can Modify This To Change How It Rounds.\n          System.out.println(xrounded);    // This Will Now Print Out The Rounded, Random Number.\n     }\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
